---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { APPS, SEGMENTS, USE_CASES, allPaths, description, pageTitle, siteFromHost } from '../content';
const site = siteFromHost();
const path = '';
const title = pageTitle(site, path);
const desc = description(site, path);
const recommended = APPS.filter(a => a.channels.includes(site.channel) || a.channels.includes('marketing')).slice(0,10);
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path="/">
  <section class="relative overflow-hidden border-b border-cyan-300/20 bg-[radial-gradient(circle_at_15%_10%,#0e7490,transparent_30%),radial-gradient(circle_at_85%_5%,#4f46e5,transparent_28%),linear-gradient(135deg,#020617,#0f172a_52%,#111827)] py-20 md:py-28">
    <div class="container grid gap-10 lg:grid-cols-[1.1fr_.9fr] lg:items-center">
      <div>
        <span class="badge">Shopify growth command center · 2026</span>
        <h1 class="hero-title mt-6">Best {site.primaryKeyword} for building a real revenue operating system</h1>
        <p class="mt-7 max-w-3xl text-xl text-slate-300">{site.heroPromise} This rebuild treats the marketing stack like a control room rather than a shelf of identical badges: one app captures demand, another converts hesitation, another keeps customers buying, and the best stack makes every channel share context.</p>
        <div class="mt-9 flex flex-wrap gap-3"><a class="btn btn-primary" href="/apps">Open the app roster</a><a class="btn btn-secondary" href="/compare">Read battlecards</a></div>
      </div>
      <div class="panel rounded-[2rem] p-6 shadow-2xl shadow-black/40">
        <div class="grid grid-cols-2 gap-3 text-sm">
          <div class="stat"><div class="text-3xl font-black text-white">{allPaths().length}</div><div class="mt-1 text-slate-300">indexable paths</div></div>
          <div class="stat"><div class="text-3xl font-black text-white">7</div><div class="mt-1 text-slate-300">stack jobs</div></div>
          <div class="stat"><div class="text-3xl font-black text-white">90d</div><div class="mt-1 text-slate-300">implementation lens</div></div>
          <div class="stat"><div class="text-3xl font-black text-white">0</div><div class="mt-1 text-slate-300">generic senders</div></div>
        </div>
        <h2 class="mt-6 text-3xl font-black text-white">Quick verdict: Shopify-native marketing beats disconnected campaigns.</h2>
        <p class="mt-4 text-slate-300">{site.bestOverallReason} A useful marketing app reads the store: products viewed, orders placed, discounts used, subscription windows, review status, loyalty tier, and the next action the customer is likely to take.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-16">
    <div class="mb-8 flex flex-col justify-between gap-5 md:flex-row md:items-end"><div><span class="badge">Ranked shortlist</span><h2 class="section-title mt-4">Apps to evaluate first</h2></div><a class="link" href="/apps">View every review →</a></div>
    <div class="grid gap-5 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-5">{recommended.map((app, i) => <a class="card" href={`/apps/${app.slug}`}><div class="text-sm font-black text-cyan-200">#{i+1} · {app.category}</div><h3 class="mt-3 text-2xl font-black text-white">{app.name}</h3><p class="mt-3 text-sm text-slate-300">{app.bestFor}</p><p class="mt-4 text-sm font-black text-cyan-100">{app.pricing}</p></a>)}</div>
  </section>

  <section class="border-y border-cyan-300/20 bg-slate-950/70 py-16">
    <div class="container grid gap-10 lg:grid-cols-[.8fr_1.2fr]">
      <div><span class="badge">Long-form operating thesis</span><h2 class="section-title mt-4">Do not buy a stack until you know the job of every layer.</h2></div>
      <div class="prose-shopify">
        <p>Most ugly Shopify app comparison pages reduce marketing to logos, star ratings, and recycled blurbs. That is not how a merchant actually chooses software. A store needs a capture layer for visitors who are not ready to buy, a merchandising layer that makes offers visible without cheapening the brand, a lifecycle layer that moves customers through welcome, cart recovery, post-purchase, replenishment, VIP, and winback, a proof layer that turns reviews and UGC into conversion assets, and a measurement layer that explains whether revenue was created or merely attributed.</p>
        <p>The best {site.keywordPlural} therefore earn their place by connecting behavior to action. If a shopper viewed a replenishable product, the app should know when that product usually runs out. If a high-AOV shopper hesitated, the follow-up should answer risk, quality, returns, financing, and proof before reaching for a discount. If a VIP customer buys every launch, the system should treat that person like inventory deserves them: early access, controlled urgency, and messages that do not look like the same coupon everyone else received.</p>
        <p>This site now uses a command-center visual system and deeper page copy so each route can function as a decision memo. The goal is not to make every app sound equal. The goal is to help a Shopify operator ask sharper questions: what data is available, what work is required, what flow should launch first, what failure mode is common, and which app will still be manageable when the catalog, customer file, and campaign calendar all get heavier.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-16"><div class="mb-8"><span class="badge">Use-case playbooks</span><h2 class="section-title mt-4">Marketing plays by lifecycle moment</h2></div><div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-4">{USE_CASES.slice(0,12).map(u=><a class="card" href={`/use-cases/${u.slug}`}><h3 class="text-xl font-black text-white">{u.name}</h3><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-300">Use the stack to {u.job}, then measure margin, retention, and customer quality instead of vanity engagement.</p></a>)}</div></section>
  <section class="container pb-16"><div class="mb-8"><span class="badge">Store-type maps</span><h2 class="section-title mt-4">Recommendations change by business model</h2></div><div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-3">{SEGMENTS.map(s=><a class="card" href={`/for/${s.slug}`}><h3 class="text-xl font-black text-white">{s.name}</h3><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-300">Prioritize app behavior around {s.pain}; generic automation will miss the commercial nuance.</p></a>)}</div></section>
  <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>How to assemble a Shopify marketing stack from this map</h2><p>This homepage treats Shopify marketing apps as a working system rather than a logo collection. A healthy stack has a capture layer for anonymous visitors, a conversion layer for product and cart hesitation, a lifecycle layer for email and SMS, a proof layer for reviews and UGC, a loyalty or referral layer when repeat behavior deserves structure, and an analytics layer that keeps the team honest about revenue quality. Not every store needs every layer on day one.</p><p>Start by identifying the most expensive leak. If traffic is high but the list is small, focus on capture and onsite offers. If carts are strong but purchases lag, focus on checkout recovery, proof, urgency, and payment objections. If first-time buyers do not return, focus on post-purchase education, replenishment, loyalty, and winback. If the team cannot explain performance, prioritize reporting before adding another channel. The right app depends on the leak, not on the most popular category in the app store.</p><p>Every app should have an owner and a first-month deliverable. Installations that begin with vague hopes usually become clutter. Define the first flow, widget, segment, report, or campaign before the subscription begins. Confirm what Shopify data the tool needs, what theme or checkout surfaces it touches, what consent rules apply, and how success will be measured after discounts and operational costs. This keeps the stack from growing faster than the team can manage.</p><p>Use the rest of the site as a decision path. App pages explain what each platform should own. Comparison pages test tradeoffs. Store-type pages translate strategy into category realities. Use-case pages show how a marketing play should be triggered, suppressed, measured, and improved. The goal is a revenue operating system that feels calmer over time: fewer disconnected campaigns, clearer customer context, better timing, and more confidence that each app earns its place.</p></article></section>
  <section class="container pb-16">
    <div class="grid gap-6 lg:grid-cols-[.95fr_1.05fr]">
      <article class="prose-shopify card">
        <h2>Stack depth: the operating map behind the rankings</h2>
        <p>A useful Shopify marketing stack starts with a commercial leak, not an app category. If visitors arrive and leave anonymously, the first layer is capture and intent. If carts stall, the stack needs proof, checkout recovery, offer control, and objection handling. If first-time buyers do not return, lifecycle email, SMS, replenishment, loyalty, and education matter more than another popup. If the team cannot explain performance, analytics and governance need attention before the next channel is added.</p>
        <p>The first month should be scoped like an implementation sprint. Week one documents every tool touching theme, checkout, forms, consent, email, SMS, reviews, loyalty, analytics, and discounting. Week two chooses one revenue moment and assigns an owner. Week three launches the play with suppression rules and QA. Week four compares platform attribution with Shopify orders, margin, customer quality, support tickets, and repeat purchase behavior. That process is slower than installing five apps at once, but it prevents stack clutter from pretending to be growth.</p>
        <h3>Marketing app scoring rubric</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Data sharing:</strong> product, customer, order, consent, review, loyalty, discount, and engagement context can move into the decision moment.</li>
          <li><strong>Commercial ownership:</strong> each app has one clear job, owner, and first-month deliverable.</li>
          <li><strong>Risk control:</strong> theme impact, duplicate offers, overlapping campaigns, attribution inflation, and consent problems are visible.</li>
          <li><strong>Iteration speed:</strong> a small team can inspect real customer paths, adjust rules, refresh creative, and read results weekly.</li>
        </ul>
      </article>
      <div class="grid gap-4">
        <div class="card"><h3 class="text-2xl font-black text-white">Example stack for abandoned cart</h3><p class="mt-3 text-slate-300">Use onsite proof and payment reassurance before the exit, email for product detail and social proof, SMS only for urgent checkout intent, and analytics to compare recovered margin with discount cost.</p></div>
        <div class="card"><h3 class="text-2xl font-black text-white">Example stack for repeat purchase</h3><p class="mt-3 text-slate-300">Combine post-purchase education, replenishment timing, loyalty status, review collection, and category-specific merchandising so a second purchase feels timely rather than forced.</p></div>
        <div class="card"><h3 class="text-2xl font-black text-white">Example stack for product launches</h3><p class="mt-3 text-slate-300">Segment waitlists, VIPs, recent buyers, and discount shoppers; coordinate email, SMS, onsite banners, inventory, reviews, and reporting before launch-day pressure arrives.</p></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* HERMES_HOME_DEEP_PASS_JULY5 */}
  <section class="container pb-16">
    <article class="prose-shopify card">
      <h2>How this marketing-stack audit desk separates serious tools from thin directories</h2>
      <p>The homepage is meant to be a working buyer map, not a listicle with swapped logos. Every recommendation starts from the same question: can a Shopify merchant use the tool to improve capture, email, SMS, reviews, loyalty, merchandising, analytics, onsite proof, and campaign governance without creating more weekly cleanup? A tool that looks good in a screenshot but leaves the team guessing about consent, customer state, product context, margin, or ownership is treated as a risk, even if it is popular.</p>
      <p>The scoring favors operational evidence. A growth lead should be able to name the first workflow to launch, the audience that deserves it, the customers to suppress, the product fields that change the message, the metric that proves quality, and the person who will review it next week. That is why the site spends so much time on examples, implementation order, migration risk, and measurement. Those are the details that separate a useful marketing app from another app subscription.</p>
      <p>The biggest failure mode is adding another dashboard that overlaps existing tools without improving ownership. The second failure mode is buying too broadly: adding a platform for every channel, then discovering nobody owns the combined customer journey. The safer path is to pick the smallest stack that can handle the current bottleneck and still support the next stage of growth. For some stores that means Sequenzy as a lean lifecycle layer. For others it means a mature platform with deeper data controls. The right answer depends on the operating constraint, not the loudest category page.</p>
      <p>Use the site like a due-diligence checklist. Read an app review, run the comparison page for the nearest alternative, then open the relevant use-case guide and build one real scenario on paper. If the tool cannot pass that scenario, the ranking should not matter. If it passes and the economics work against incremental revenue, app cost, speed to launch, repeat behavior, margin, support load, and whether a named owner can run the workflow, it belongs on the shortlist.</p>
    </article>
  </section>

</BaseLayout>
